{"timestamp": "2025-12-06 11:46:58.697683", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nScope and objective\n- Validate end-to-end health for DHCP, DNS, OSPF routing, and web access paths.\n- Detect anomalies, localize faulty devices, and identify root causes.\n- No remediation actions are proposed.\n\nHigh-level health summary\n- Server farm (10.200.0.0/24): Healthy. Intra-server and server-to-LB reachability is good. DNS server reachable. Load balancer reachable and serving HTTP.\n- Access subnet 10.1.1.0/24 (site 1_1): Healthy. Host obtained DHCP, has default route, and can reach/load-balance HTTP services.\n- Access subnet 10.2.1.0/24 (site 2_1): Unhealthy. Host has link but no IP address. DHCP appears to be failing at the distribution layer due to inactive DHCP relay.\n- OSPF: Appears healthy end-to-end; routes are present on distribution routers to server farm and peer subnets.\n\nDetailed findings and evidence\n\n1) DHCP/Host L3 state\n- host_1_1_1_1 (10.1.1.0/24):\n  - Has DHCP lease: inet 10.1.1.10/24 dynamic; default via 10.1.1.1.\n  - Can reach load balancer and web servers:\n    - Ping to 10.200.0.7 (LB) and 10.200.0.4 successful (0% loss; ~3 ms RTT).\n    - HTTP to http://web99.local succeeds with sub-second TTFB and ~1.0–1.1 s total per request (3 trials).\n- host_2_1_1_1 (10.2.1.0/24):\n  - Link up but no IPv4 address assigned; no routes. ip addr shows no inet on eth0; ip route is empty.\n  - ethtool indicates link detected (10G/full), so L2 appears fine on host/switch segment.\n  - In reachability matrix, host_2_1_1_1 tests are status unknown (no IP).\n\n2) Distribution layer (focus on DHCP relay)\n- router_dist_2_1 (serving 10.2.1.0/24):\n  - L2/L3:\n    - br0 has 10.2.1.1/24, eth1 enslaved to br0, consistent with bridging to access switch.\n    - OSPF routes installed to 10.200.0.0/24 and other infra; can ping DHCP server 10.200.0.8 (1.5–2.7 ms).\n  - DHCP relay services:\n    - isc-dhcp-relay: Active: inactive (dead).\n    - dhcrelay: no active service output.\n  - Implication: Broadcast DHCP from 10.2.1.0/24 is not being relayed to the central DHCP server despite L3 reachability being fine.\n- router_dist_1_1 (serving 10.1.1.0/24):\n  - isc-dhcp-relay reported inactive as well. However, a host in this subnet has an active dynamic lease (valid_lft ~58s at time of capture), so either:\n    - An alternative relay mechanism/service is in place not visible under isc-dhcp-relay/dhcrelay; or\n    - The lease was previously obtained and not yet expired. This does not currently present a user-facing issue in 10.1.1.0/24.\n\n3) Server farm, DNS, and load balancer\n- dns_server (10.200.0.2) reachability to LB and web servers is OK (0% loss; ~1–2.5 ms RTT).\n- Web servers 10.200.0.3–.6 and load_balancer 10.200.0.7 can reach each other with low-latency pings.\n- From host_1_1_1_1:\n  - HTTP to web99.local works; name resolution is fast (name lookup ~3–5 ms), connect ~5–7 ms; total ~1.0–1.1 s per request.\n  - Direct IP reachability to web_server_1 (10.200.0.4) is successful, consistent with design allowing access to Apache web servers web0.local…web3.local.\n- Note: Backend web servers behind the LB are by design not directly accessible from hosts. No direct backend hostnames were available in the test harness; no evidence suggests backend exposure.\n\n4) OSPF/routing posture\n- router_dist_2_1 OSPF routes include:\n  - 10.200.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.8 (core), and peer subnets via OSPF; kernel routes for local 10.2.1.0/24.\n- Given end-to-end reachability from multiple nodes to 10.200.0.0/24 and between cores/distributions, OSPF appears operational.\n\nAnomalies detected\n- Access subnet 10.2.1.0/24: Host cannot obtain an IP address due to DHCP failure.\n- On router_dist_2_1, DHCP relay service is not running despite L3 reachability to the DHCP server. This prevents DHCP broadcasts from 10.2.1.0/24 from reaching 10.200.0.8.\n\nFault localization\n- Primary fault domain: router_dist_2_1 (distribution block for 10.2.1.0/24).\n- Affected device: router_dist_2_1.\n- Unaffected comparable domain: router_dist_1_1 currently serving 10.1.1.0/24 where a host has an active lease and full reachability.\n\nRoot cause assessment\n- DHCP relay on router_dist_2_1 is inactive (isc-dhcp-relay inactive, no alternative dhcrelay detected). With no relay, clients in 10.2.1.0/24 cannot reach the centralized DHCP server to obtain leases, resulting in host_2_1_1_1 having no IP address despite link being up and routing being otherwise healthy.\n\nNon-issues / confirmations\n- Core/distribution OSPF: Functional.\n- Server farm reachability: Functional.\n- DNS resolution via local DNS server: Functional for web99.local (as evidenced by curl timing).\n- Load balancer: Reachable and responsive from host_1_1_1_1.\n\nEnd of report.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 8321, "output_tokens": 4647, "total_tokens": 12968, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 6528}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 3264}}}
